# New Page SEO & Sitemap Checklist

When creating or modifying any `page.tsx` in `apps/web/src/app/`, you **must** complete every item below before considering the task done.

## 1. Page-Level Metadata (mandatory)

Every `page.tsx` must export a `metadata` object (or `generateMetadata` for dynamic pages):

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from "next";

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: "Page Title — TrustLink | <Primary Keyword>",
  description: "<120–155 chars incorporating 1-2 target keywords naturally>",
  openGraph: {
    title: "...",
    description: "...",
  },
};
```

- **Title formula:** `Descriptive Title — TrustLink | Primary Keyword`
- **Description:** 120–155 characters, includes at least one primary keyword and one secondary keyword.
- Target keyword bank: "Blockchain Background Verification India", "Instant Employee Verification API", "Eliminate Resume Fraud", "DPDP Compliant HR Tech", "Digital Experience Letter", "Automated Employee Offboarding", "Self-Sovereign Identity Careers", "Reduce Time-to-Hire".

## 2. Sitemap Entry (mandatory)

After creating a new public-facing page, add an entry to `apps/web/src/app/sitemap.ts`:

```tsx
{
  url: `${BASE_URL}/<new-route>`,
  lastModified: now,
  changeFrequency: "weekly",   // or "monthly" for low-change pages
  priority: 0.7,               // 1.0 = homepage, 0.8 = conversion, 0.5 = support pages
}
```

**Do NOT skip this step.** If the page is not in the sitemap, search engines will not discover it reliably.

## 3. Semantic HTML Heading Hierarchy

- Exactly **one `<h1>`** per page, incorporating primary keyword.
- Subsections use `<h2>` → `<h3>` in order. Never skip levels.

## 4. Internal Links Use `next/link`

All internal route links must use `<Link>` from `next/link` (see Section 7 of instructions.md). Anchor links (`#section`) may use `<a>`.

## 5. Self-Check Prompt

After finishing, verify:
- "Did I add metadata with keywords to this page?" — if no, add it.
- "Did I add this route to sitemap.ts?" — if no, add it.
- "Does my h1 contain a target keyword?" — if no, revise it.
